ourse offerings page to determine if the below courses are offered in your intended Study Abroad term.   Principles of Biology I  Principles of Biology II  Molecular Cellular Biology I: Cellular Biochemistry and Molecular Biology  Molecular Cellular Biology II: Cellular Structure and Function  Basic Human Anatomy    James Cooke University, Townsville, Australia   [Enrolled through Arcadia University’s College of Global Studies]   Cell Biology  Medical Laboratory Science Molecular and Cell Biology Honours  Molecular and Cell Biology Honours Part 1 of 2  Molecular and Cell Biology Honours Part 2 of 2  Introductory Biochemistry and Microbiology  Conservation Biology  Functional Biology of Marine Organisms  Invertebrate Biology  Marine Conservation Biology  Introductory Infectious Diseases and Immunobiology  Marine Microbiology  Clinical Microbiology  Advanced Immunobiology  Medical Laboratory Science Microbiology Honours  Microbiology and Immunology Honours Part 1 of 2  Microbiology and Immunology Honours Part 2 of 2  General Pathobiology  Cognitive Neuroscience: The Biology of Mind    University of the South Pacific, Suva, Fiji   [Enrolled through the University of Wisconsin-Platteville]    General Biology  Animal Biology  General Ecology  Invertebrate Biology  Genetics and Evolution  Quantitative Biology  Tropical Plant Biology  Plant Physiology  Conservation Biology  Marine Biology  Fish and Fisheries Biology  Environmental and Marine Microbiology  Comparative Animal Physiology  Advanced Environment Microbiology  Advanced Physiology  Research Project in Biology  Molecular Biology  Advanced Food Processing and Industrial Marketing  Biodiversity and Conservation    Danish Institute for Study Abroad (Copenhagen & Stockholm)   [DIS is an independent study abroad organization that offers courses taught by faculty at Universities in Denmark and Sweden in addition to professional practitioners, e.g. in the medical, business, and architectural fields. The DIS US school of record is the University of Minnesota.]  Copenhagen   Biological Conservation and Biodiversity  Biological Conservation and Biodiversity Lab  Biology of Marine Mammals  Cell Factories: Design, Engineering, and Analysis  Cognitive Neuroscience of Consciousness  Cognitive Neuroscience of Consciousness Research Lab  Complexity of Cancer  Diabetes: Diagnoses and Diseases  Epigenetics and the Environment  Human Health and Disease: A Clinical Approach  Immunology  Medical Biotechnology and Drug Development  Neurological Disorders and Diseases  Neuroplasticity: From Neurons to Behavior  Neuroplasticity of Pain  Neuroscience of Fear  Neuroscience of Religion and Atheism  Philosophy of Mental Health  Psychopharmacology: Substances and the Brain  Public Mental Health  Science Research Practicum  The Ethical Brain: Philosophy and Neuroscience  The Social Brain: Neuropsychology of Social Behaviors   Stockholm   Immunology and Infectious Diseases  Tumor Biology and Oncology  The Developing Brain: From Infancy to Adolescence  Public Health Policy in Practice: Scandinavian Case Studies    World Learning / SIT (School for International Training)   [World Learning’s academic programs offered through SIT (founded as the School for International Training) are accredited by the New England Association of Schools and Colleges.] The semester programs include an embedded undergraduate research component. See The SIT Digital Collection to browse samples of student research work.  Public Health   ADD: India: Public Health, Gender, and Community Action  Switzerland: Global Health and Development Policy   Natural and Human Ecology   Australia: Rainforest, Reef, and Cultural Ecology  Australia: Sustainability and Environmental Action  Ecuador: Comparative Ecology and Conservation  Iceland and Greenland: Climate Change and the Arctic    The School for Field Studies (SFS)   [SFS has direct affiliation with over 50 colleges and universities, and students from these schools typically direct credit for SFS courses. All other students are registered at and receive credit from the University of Minnesota, which accredits SFS programs. The semester programs include an embedded undergraduate research component. The student Directed Research (DR) projects are the culmination and highlight of the semester program. This list of recent Student Directed Research Projects provides a snapshot of recent titles by program, home institution, and student.  Environmental Field Studies at 7 Research Stations   Rainforest Studies …Australia & New Zealand  Himalayan Studies …Bhutan  River Ecosystems & Conservation…Cambodia  Sustainable Development …Costa Rica  Tropical Island …Panama  Biodiversity & Development …Peru  Marine Resource Studies …Turks & Caicos Islands    SFS Examples of Student Directed Research Projects Fall 2015    Tropical Rainforest Studies: Australia   Microhabitat preferences of the Lumholtz’s tree-kangaroo ( Dendrolagus lumholtzi ) in soil nutrients and forest structure. Michael Rockwell [University of Michigan]   Taking the heat: Tooth-billed Bowerbirds' potential resilience to climate change impacts. Madison Wanamaker [Dickinson College]     Himalayan Studies: Bhutan   Floristic Biodiversity Characterization of Ugyen Wangchuck Institute for Conservation and Environment (UWICE) Forest Research Preserve. Gabriela D’Elia [Seattle University]   Effects of community-based management practices on biodiversity. Molly Tankersley [Northeastern University]   Mekong Studies: Cambodia   Morphology and Niche Partitioning of Fish Assemblage in the Tonle Sap Biosphere Reserve. Lan Nguyen [Hollins University]   Structure of Fish Assemblages and Catch per Unit Effort of Cambodia’s Tonle Sap Lake. Ben Stablow [Montana State University]   Sustainable Development Studies: Costa Rica   Effects of plant functional traits on C/N ratios in tropical pasture soils. Jessica O’Toole [University of Denver]   Tropical Island Biodiversity Studies: Panama   Comparative Soil Health via Abiotic Indicators on Cacao Farms in the Bocas del Toro Archipelago, Panama. Caitlin Reilly [Davidson College]   Life History Biomass and Foraging of Sparisoma viride as Indicators of MPA Success in the Bocas del Toro, Panama. Bridget Austin [Franklin & Marshall College]   Andes-Amazon Studies: Peru   Secondary metabolites with a phytoprotective role in scaly tree ferns, Cyatheaceae , narrowly distributed along elevational gradients in an Andean-Amazonian basin of western Peru. Kalley Guerdet [University of Minnesota]   Oleoresin Antipathogen Response Success May Affect Altitudinal Distribution in Tree Fern ( Cyatheales ) Species of the Southwestern Amazon. Erika Weiskopf [Swarthmore College]   Marine Resource Studies: Turks & Caicos Islands   The role Hermodice carunculata and Coralliophila abbreviata play in the condition of the Acroporid species, South Caicos, Turks and Caicos Islands. Laura Adair [Guilford College]   Assessment of the Relationship between Habitat Complexity and Indicator Species Diadema antillarum and Panulirus argus in the Reef System surrounding South Caicos, Turks and Caicos Islands, British West Indies. Sophia Emmons [Davidson College]       © Copyright 2014-2020 The Board of Trustees of the University of Illinois     Footer Navigation                    Vice Provost for Global Engagement  Office of External Scholarships  Office of Financial Aid  University Registrar  Centers for Diversity  Disability Resources  Privacy Policy  Contact Us     Translate »  Cookie Settings 